How to modify and add new menus
===============================

The following is a more or less detailed explanation for those 
of you that feel confident enough to add menus and menu-items. One of 
the biggest advantages of this method is that unlike many programs, 
this is an AmigaOS friendly implementation that does not require 
external programs and can even work on plain 68000 Amigas.

The limitations are that you cannot modify "Workbench", "Windows", and 
"Icons" menus in any way. But you can add menu items to the "Tools" 
menu, and add other new Menus and submenu items.

Be careful to always respect the quotes and format. The only statement 
that can be omitted is the HOTKEY one. The MenuTools syntax for each 
entry will be explained in the following example:


               REFERENCE NOTE     MENU ITEM NAME    HOTKEY                                   SHELL COMMANDLINE
                     |                  |             |                                              |
              +-------------+     +------------+ +----------+                        +--------------------------------+
 MENU ADD NAME MenuMultiView TITLE '"MultiView"' SHORTCUT 'W' CMD "'address command ''C:WBLoad SYS:Utilities/MultiView'''"
                        
                        
REFERENCE NOTE 
This is a single word whose only purpose is to remind you what the 
menu item does. It has no real functionality beyond that.

MENU ITEM NAME 
This is the name that will be displayed in the Tools menu. You can add 
new menus and submenu items by using the backwards slash bar ( for 
e.g.: \Menu-Name\Menu-Item\Submenu-item ).

HOTKEY
This is an optional statement that points to a shortcut that you can 
set in which the [Amiga] key and another character that you are 
allowed to define is always involved. Be careful when adding a 
shortcut to verify that it is not being used by AmigaOS or any other 
running programs or you may end up causing conflicts between them.
         
SHELL COMMANDLINE 
This is the action you wish to be executed. It must be a Shell 
command, an ARexx script, a Shell script or it can even be a Workbench 
program if you are smart enough to use the WBLoad command.
